entry.title: Project Report
entry.summary:
In this notebook, you'll sumarize your finding for the class presentation.

The class presentation will use this notebook in slide mode, as I do during lecture time.

You'll need to download the following zip file, unzip it, and run the following notebook install-support.ipynb to install the slide capabilities.

The notebook notebook-slideshow-example.ipynb will give you examples on how to use slides within the iPython notebook.

You should also write this notebook so that you can convert it nicely into a pdf document using the commands

ipython nbconvert NB4_report.pynb --to latex
pdflatex NB4_report.tex

See here for further references on how to do that.

In this notebook, you'll

  • describe your problem as stated in the propectus

  • comment on your data sources, on their format, on the difficulties to get them

  • present the main challenge you encountered

  • present your finding in the form of expresive graphics

Be sure to include an introduction section motivating your visualizations, with a description of the substantive context and why it is interesting.

Cite the source of the data and any other references that you used in carrying out your project.

Team Red Bear: Correlations Between Obesity and Socioeconomic Factors in American Counties

Project by Ha Ngyuen, Jaehak Yu, Micky Wong

Stat 133: Professor Benoit Dherin

May 4, 2014

Team members responsible for this notebook:

List the team members contributing to this notebook, along with their responsabilities:

  • Team member 1 Jaehak Yu — Responsible for summarizing prospectus problems and editing
  • Team member 2 Ha Nguyen — Responsible for describing data sources and their format
  • Team member 3 Micky Wong — Responsible for presenting main challenges encountered and presenting graphics

I advise you to work at least in pairs for each project notebook, as you did for the homework assignments. Of course, all team members may participate to each notebook.

Prospectus Summarization and Main Challenges

As stated in our prospectus, we originally set out to find the correlation between obesity and various socioeconomic factors such as education levels, population density, poverty levels, etc.

To do so, we realized that we would need a large amount of data to find strong enough correlations. As such, a state by state basis wouldn't cut it. We needed to go deeper and find data on a county level. As such, we gathered data from over 3000 US counties on each of the variables we chose to examine.

Additionally, given the size of the data, we were initially concerned with removing all discrepancies. For instance, among the 3000+ US counties we had data on, there were various NA or missing values within the lists. This was so because some counties were too small to have data recorded. So for examples, poverty levels were recorded in some counties and not others.

As a result, we had to be very meticulous in gathering all NA or missing value counties and eliminating them from the data analysis. While doing so brought down our total number of counties analyzed to 2000+, we feel that this was a better outcome for a few reasons. Primarily, it removed the small, insignificant counties that were far more likely to contain bizarre outliers as a result of their size. Second, 2000+ counties was still a very significant amount of data points to analyze considering the different number of variables we were looking at.

Finally, we were considered about the initial assumptions made in isolating some variables and reading into what our data tells us. While using regression can tell us that there is a relationship between, say, poverty and obesity, we also know that correlation does not equal causation.

When coming out with our results and summarizing them, we had to be careful not to assign definitive causation to any strong correlation we found. So while our results would certainly be more definitive and eye-popping if we could assert that X or Y caused obesity, we were careful to make sure not to fall into such traps.

Our Data Sources

Our data came primarily from www.data.gov — the US government's database on information regarding US states, counties, and municipalities. As it's from an official government database, all data is both accurate, reliable, and up-to-date.

From this site we downloaded a number of files regarding health and other information on US counties. These files included and were called:

  1. Demographics: This file presented a demographic breakdown of the counties; from this file we took out "poverty rates", "population size", and "population density" as variables to be isolated and compared.

  2. Summary Measures of Health: This file presented various health statistics about each county; from this file we took out "average life expectancy", "health status", and "number of unhealthy days" out to be compared.

  3. Risk Factors and Access to Care: This file examined various risk factors among the population in each county along with their ability to access medical care; from this we took out "Uninsured Rate", "Number of Smokers", "Obesity Rate", and "Number of Primary Care Physicians per 100,000" to evaluate.

  4. Vulnerable Populations and Environmental Health: This file presented the number of "vulnerable" populations in the counties as well as the health of their surroundings (pollution); from this we took out "Rate of People w/o a High School Diploma", "Unemployment Rate", "Depression Rate", "People with Recent Drug Use".

That was a total of 14 different variables evaluated. Originally the data all came in XLS form which we converted to CSV. Finally, because all the data was so consolidated in one central location at www.data.gov, we actually found that gathering the data was rather easy. The more difficult part was simply choosing which variables to isolate.

Our Findings in Visualizations and Numbers

In looking at the numbers themselves, these were our findings:

In []: 
"""
Call:
lm(formula = df$obesity ~ ., data = df)

Residuals:
    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
-13.578  -2.090   0.017   2.088  13.912 

Coefficients:
                          Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept)              6.843e+01  5.207e+00  13.142  < 2e-16 ***
population_size         -6.076e-07  2.302e-07  -2.640  0.00835 ** 
population_density      -1.083e-04  4.008e-05  -2.704  0.00692 ** 
poverty                  1.835e-01  3.919e-02   4.683 3.01e-06 ***
avg_life_expectancy     -5.142e-01  6.297e-02  -8.166 5.48e-16 ***
unhealthy_days          -6.886e-03  9.444e-02  -0.073  0.94189    
health_status            2.186e-01  2.746e-02   7.961 2.80e-15 ***
uninsured_rate          -2.121e-01  3.169e-02  -6.693 2.81e-11 ***
smoker                   3.088e-02  1.860e-02   1.660  0.09706 .  
primary_care_physicians -1.417e-02  2.065e-03  -6.864 8.84e-12 ***
no_HS_diploma_rate      -1.102e-02  2.656e-02  -0.415  0.67842    
unemployed_rate          1.017e+00  1.309e-01   7.768 1.24e-14 ***
depression_rate         -1.079e+00  1.270e-01  -8.496  < 2e-16 ***
drug_rate               -6.898e-01  7.194e-02  -9.589  < 2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 ‘***’ 0.001 ‘**’ 0.01 ‘*’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘ ’ 1

Residual standard error: 3.484 on 2066 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.4623,	Adjusted R-squared:  0.4589 
F-statistic: 136.6 on 13 and 2066 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
"""

The above summary shows that factors like Poverty, Average Life Expectancy, Health Status, Uninsured Rate, Primary Care Physicians, Unemployment Rate, Depression Rate and Drug Rate correlate most strongly with obesity. There was also Population Size and Population Density correlating with obesity as well.

What was surprising to us, however, was the lack of strong correlation between smokers (as we thought engaging in risky health behavior like smoking would increase obesity) and a lack of High School education with obesity.

As it turns out, smoking is actually an appetite suppressant, which was interesting information for us personally.

Visualizations Continued

We then look at various visualizations of the factors we evaluated.

In [12]: 
from IPython.display import Image
In [14]: 
Image(url='http://imgur.com/tqVrJKZ.png')
Out[14]:

Along with a comparison with residuals

In [15]: 
Image('http://imgur.com/WX4agzl.png')
Out[15]:

Here we can see rather strange looking graphs on Population Size and Population Density. This is so because Population Size and Population Density varies significantly by county. So while other factors we isolated were looking at rates per county, these two factors are looking at sheer size, hence their unique presentaiton on the graphs.

Final Summary of the Data

All in all we find out a few things about the variables:

Positive Correlations (Ex: Higher the poverty rate, higher the obesity rate)

  1. Poverty: porverty rate per US county
  2. Health Status: rate of population who report "poor" health
  3. Unemployment Rate: unemployment rate per US county

Negative Correlations

  1. Population Size
  2. Population Density
  3. Average Life Expectancy
  4. Uninsured Rate
  5. Primary Care Physicians per 100,000 People
  6. Depression Rate
  7. Recent Drug Use Rate

With the correlations we see, this is the final conclusion we have come to. Rural areas have higher correlation with obesity than urban areas would (which is consistent with research we found online). Additionally we see that poverty levels and unemployment rates have positive correlations with obesity. We also see that uninsured rates and the number of primary care physicians per 100,000 people have negative correlations with obesity.

With all this in mind, we see that a lack of access (shown by primary care physicians, uninsurance rates) and an inability to utilize existing resources (shown by poverty, unemployment rates) have high correlations with obesity. While we will not outright make a claim that it causes obesity, our data shows that there are visible correlations between the factors.

entry.title: Data Cleaning
entry.summary:
In this notebook, you'll

  • load the raw data into R or Pandas dataframe from the ./data/raw directory using the functions and classes (written during the data gathering phase) in the ./script directory

  • perform visual exploration on your data variables to detect anomalies, errors, outliers, interesting features etc.

  • clean categorical and quantitative variables (by removing observations and variables with too many missing values, by consolidating categorical variables, by selecting an appropriate subset of variables and observations for later analysis, etc.)

  • save the cleaned data into csv files in the ./data/cleaned directory

  • save interesting graphics you obtained during visual exploration into the ./visualiation directory

Team members responsible for this notebook:

List the team members contributing to this notebook, along with their responsabilities:

  • Team Member 1: Jaehak Yu — Responsible for isolating the variables we find interesting and noting which rows have NA values
  • Team Member 2: Ha Nguyen — Responsible for converting isolated variables into rates/percentages for good data comparison and compiling all variables into a cleaned table
  • Team Member 3: Micky Wong — Responsible for removing the NA rows from the cleaned table and uploading it as a csv file into the ./data/cleaned folder

I advise you to work at least in pairs for each project notebook, as you did for the homework assignments. Of course, all team members may participate to each notebook.

Example¶

Here I'll load the plant data in xml format into a R data frame using the

create_df_from_plant_xml(file)

function contained in the R script

    ./script/plant_df-R
In []: 
%load_ext rmagic

To load the function into a R cell, one needs to use the

source(R_script_file)

command in R, which works in a similar way as the

import module

command in Python:

In []: 
%%R
source('./script/plant_df-R')

Now, we can create a data frame directly from the XML file using the functin contained in the scrip above.

If you wish to perform the cleaning using Pandas data frames instead of R data frames, one make the R data frame available to Python cells by using the R magic command:

%%R -d df_name

To know more on how to pass variables back and forth between R and Python cells, please have a look at the notebook here.

In []: 
%%R -d data

library(XML)

data = create_df_from_plant_xml('./data/raw/plant.xml')

Now let's load our data into a Pandas data frame:

In []: 
from pandas import DataFrame

df = DataFrame(data)
df.head()

The actual data cleaning can now begins!

Team Red Bear: Data Cleaning¶

As we loaded our files as CSV files to begin with, there was no need to transform XML or XLS files into CSV. Instead we start off immediately with the data analysis. The files we have chosen to look into from the original data provided were:

  1. Demographics (Population Size, Population Density, Poverty Levels)
  2. Summary Measures of Health (Average Life Expectancy, Health Status, Number of Unhealthy Days)
  3. Vulnerable Populations and Environmental Health (Percentage without High School Diplomas, Unemployment Rate, Recent Drug Use, Major Depression)
  4. Risk Factors and Access to Care (Obesity, Uninsured Rate, Smokers Rate, Primary Care Physicians per 100,000)

This is a total of 13 variables to evaluate.

We start now with loading the files into dataframes. First, with the demographics file we target the relevant columns.

In [121]: 
%load_ext rmagic
In [122]: 
%%R
demographics = read.csv('./data/raw/demographics.csv')

population_size = demographics[['Population_Size']]

population_density = demographics[['Population_Density']]

poverty = demographics[['Poverty']]

county_names = demographics[['CHSI_County_Name']]

Because some counties are small, we find that there are NA values (demarked as -2222) in both the Population Density and Poverty data. But because every list much be cleaned, we gather first the indexes of the NA values within each list in order to clean all the lists at once.

In [123]: 
%%R
NA_poverty = which(poverty < 0)
NA_population_density = which(population_density < 0)
NA_population_size = which(population_size < 0)

Now that we know what the indexes within the demographics file, we add it into a list of which indexes are demarked as NA. Once compiling the total list of all values we will remove all the NA files from every single column in the final cleaned version.

In [124]: 
%%R
NA_list = c(NA_poverty, NA_population_density, NA_population_size)
print(NA_list)

[1] 547 250

We then proceed with what we've been doing to every other file of interest.

In [125]: 
%%R
summary = read.csv('./data/raw/summarymeasuresofhealth.csv')


avg_life_expectancy = summary[['ALE']]

health_status = summary[['Health_Status']]

unhealthy_days = summary[['Unhealthy_Days']]


NA_ALE = which(avg_life_expectancy < 0)

NA_health_status = which(health_status < 0)

NA_unhealthy_days = which(unhealthy_days < 0)


NA_list = c(NA_list, NA_ALE, NA_health_status, NA_unhealthy_days)
In [126]: 
%%R
risk = read.csv('./data/raw/riskfactorsandaccesstocare.csv')


uninsured = risk[['Uninsured']]

smoker = risk[['Smoker']]

obesity = risk[['Obesity']]

primary_care_physicians = risk[['Prim_Care_Phys_Rate']]


NA_uninsured = which(uninsured < 0)

NA_smoker = which(smoker < 0)

NA_obesity = which(obesity < 0)

NA_primary_care = which(primary_care_physicians < 0)
In [127]: 
%%R
NA_list = c(NA_list, NA_uninsured, NA_smoker, NA_obesity, NA_primary_care)
In [128]: 
%%R
vulnerable = read.csv('./data/raw/vulnerablepopsandenvhealth.csv')


no_HS_diploma = vulnerable[['No_HS_Diploma']]

unemployed = vulnerable[['Unemployed']]

depression = vulnerable[['Major_Depression']]

drugs = vulnerable[['Recent_Drug_Use']]


NA_diploma = which(no_HS_diploma < 0)

NA_unemployed = which(unemployed < 0)

NA_depression = which(depression < 0)

NA_drugs = which(drugs < 0)
In [129]: 
%%R
NA_list = c(NA_list, NA_diploma, NA_unemployed, NA_depression, NA_drugs)
In [1]: 
%%R
NA_cleaned_list = unique(NA_list)
NA_final = sort(NA_cleaned_list)

ERROR: Cell magic `%%R` not found.

Now we have all the variables we want isolated, their respective information, along with the rows that contain NA values. We then combine all the variables into a table and aim to delete all such NA rows from the table so we evaluate only those counties which have data available for all variables. While we will be removing around 1000 of the counties, we believe this will actually be for the better. We have 2000 US counties remaining and those removed were simply too small for sufficient analysis. But before doing so, we convert some of the variables into rates so that they can be compared across counties without massively skewing the data.

In [131]: 
%%R
drug_rate = (drugs / population_size) * 100

depression_rate = (depression / population_size) * 100

unemployed_rate = (unemployed / population_size) * 100

no_HS_diploma_rate = (no_HS_diploma / population_size) * 100

uninsured_rate = (uninsured / population_size) * 100
In [132]: 
%%R
New_Cleaned_Table = data.frame(county_names, population_size, population_density, poverty, avg_life_expectancy, unhealthy_days, health_status, uninsured_rate, smoker, obesity, primary_care_physicians, no_HS_diploma_rate, unemployed_rate, depression_rate, drug_rate)

print(New_Cleaned_Table)

entry.title: Data Gathering
entry.summary:
In this notebook, you'll

  • create the directory structure for your project
  • download the raw data for your project
  • write functions and classes to transform raw data (e.g in XML, jason, etc.) into data frames
  • explain what your are doing

Team members responsible for this notebook:

List the team members contributing to this notebook, along with their responsabilities:

  • Team Member 1: Jaehak Yu — Responsible for locating link, isolating variables
  • Team Member 2: Ha Nguyen — Responsible for converting xls into csv
  • Team Member 3: Micky Wong — Responsible for uploading csv files into ./data/raw folder

I advise you to work at least in pairs for each project notebook, as you did for the homework assignments. Of course, all team members may participate to each notebook.

Instructions:

In markdown cells, you'll

  • list and describe the data sources for your class project
    • provide the data urls
    • describe the file formats
    • explain the data content of each file

Remark: If your data is not directly available through the web (for instance, you requested it from a company, or got it from Inna or Henry), place you data into your personal bdrive, and provide a link to it, that you'll use in this notebook to download it into the data folder, as explained below).

In code cells, you'll

  • create the following directories:

    ./data
./data/raw        # to store your raw data
./data/cleaned    # to store the cleanned data
./data/simulated  # to store simulated data
./visualizations  # to store your plots

  • display samples of your data files (e.g. for a csv files, use data frames and the head method)

  • Write scripts into the ./script directory using the he magic command

    %%file ./script/file_name

Your scripts should contain functions and objects allowing you to

  • download the actual raw data in the directory ./data/raw

  • load the downloaded the raw data files into data frames

This way, the functions and objects contained in your scripts will be accessible in other notebooks through the import command in Python (see example below).

Remark 1: In the code cells, you may use Python, R, or Bash, as you find more convenient.

Remark 2: Try to make your notebook as readable and usable (by others) as possible.

Example¶

Here is an example of how to package your code into scripts reusable in other notebook.

You'll need to do something similar to that. You'll also need to write explanations as outlined above in markdown cells.

Creating the directory structure

In [2]: 
%%bash
mkdir ../script ../data ../data/raw ../data/cleaned ../data/simulated ../visualizations
ls -r

Downloading and displaying raw data¶

In this example, I am using R. You want to use Python instead.

In [4]: 
%load_ext rmagic

TO DO: list sources, display data sample, explain data content, etc.

We now download an XML source containing plant data, and display an typical plant entry, represented as a XML node:

In [6]: 
%%R
library(XML)
plant_url  =  'http://www.stat.berkeley.edu/classes/s133/data/plant_catalog.xml'
plant_file = './data/raw/plant.xml'

download.file(plant_url, plant_file, method="curl")

xml_doc   = xmlParse(plant_file)
root_node = xmlRoot(xml_doc)

plant_nodes = xmlChildren(root_node)
print(plant_nodes[[1]])

Loading raw data into data frames¶

The dataframe column labels are the tags of the XML nodes, contained in the plant XML nodes:

In [7]: 
%%R
column_names = names(plant_nodes[[1]])
cat(column_names)

COMMON BOTANICAL ZONE LIGHT PRICE AVAILABILITY

Given a column name, we create a data frame column containing the column values:

In [11]: 
%%R
common_tag = column_names[1]

get_value = function(plant_node, tag) xmlValue(plant_node[[tag]])
    
common_column = sapply(plant_nodes, get_value, common_tag)
    
cat(common_column)

Bloodroot Columbine Marsh Marigold Cowslip Dutchman's-Breeches Ginger, Wild Hepatica Liverleaf Jack-In-The-Pulpit Mayapple Phlox, Woodland Phlox, Blue Spring-Beauty Trillium Wake Robin Violet, Dog-Tooth Trout Lily Adder's-Tongue Anemone Grecian Windflower Bee Balm Bergamot Black-Eyed Susan Buttercup Crowfoot Butterfly Weed Cinquefoil Primrose Gentian Blue Gentian Jacob's Ladder Greek Valerian California Poppy Shooting Star Snakeroot Cardinal Flower

We package the code above into a function that creates the data frame column corresponding from a tag name and a list of plant nodes:

In [12]: 
%%R
get_column = function(tag, plants) sapply(plants, get_value, tag)
    
cat((get_column('COMMON', plant_nodes)))

Bloodroot Columbine Marsh Marigold Cowslip Dutchman's-Breeches Ginger, Wild Hepatica Liverleaf Jack-In-The-Pulpit Mayapple Phlox, Woodland Phlox, Blue Spring-Beauty Trillium Wake Robin Violet, Dog-Tooth Trout Lily Adder's-Tongue Anemone Grecian Windflower Bee Balm Bergamot Black-Eyed Susan Buttercup Crowfoot Butterfly Weed Cinquefoil Primrose Gentian Blue Gentian Jacob's Ladder Greek Valerian California Poppy Shooting Star Snakeroot Cardinal Flower

We are now ready to retrieve all the columns of our data frame into a list of vectors, which we will use to construct our data frame:

In [13]: 
%%R
data = lapply(column_names, get_column, plant_nodes)

plant_df = data.frame(data, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

print(head(plant_df))

Using the data frame we just created, we save the plant data into a csv file into the raw data directory:

In [14]: 
%%R
write.csv(plant_df, './data/raw/plants_to_be_cleaned.csv')
In []: 
!head ./data/raw/plants_to_be_cleaned.csv

Packaging the gathering code into reusable functions¶

In [15]: 
%%file ./script/plant_df-R

get_value  = function(plant_node, tag) xmlValue(plant_node[[tag]])
    
get_column = function(tag, plants) sapply(plants, get_value, tag)
    
create_df_from_plant_xml = function(plant_file){
    require(XML)
    xml_doc      = xmlParse(plant_file)
    root_node    = xmlRoot(xml_doc)
    plant_nodes  = xmlChildren(root_node)
    column_names = names(plant_nodes[[1]])

    data     = lapply(column_names, get_column, plant_nodes)
    return(data.frame(data, stringsAsFactors = FALSE))
}

Writing ./script/plant_df-R

Now, our function converting a raw plant XML file into a R data frame can be used in other notebooks, using the source command:

In []: 
%%R
source('./script/plant_df-R')

print(head(create_df_from_plant_xml(plant_file)))

Team Red Bear: Data Gathering¶

First we go about by creating all the necessary files, as shown in previous examples, and to make them accessible to all who wish to utilize the same data we have.

In [11]:

mkdir ./script ./data ./data/raw ./data/cleaned ./data/simulated ./visualizations

With this complete, we proceed to download all the relevant files for the project. Each file has demographic information on over 3000 US counties along with a multitude of variables, constituting a wealth of data. By downloading all data in CSV files we create an easy and accessible source of data for everyone to work with and access.

In [22]: 
%load_ext rmagic
In [51]: 
%%R
demog_url  = 'https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/pub?key=0An-NKSZPgC0OdExrTUpIUWZUblZKVmM5YngyclhBNVE&output=csv'
demog_file = './data/raw/demographics.csv'

download.file(demog_url, demog_file, method="curl")

death_url = 'https://www.dropbox.com/s/4l566gzg5ry818b/LEADINGCAUSESOFDEATH.csv'
death_file = './data/raw/leadingcauseofdeath.csv'

download.file(death_url, death_file, method="curl", extra='-L')

measures_url = 'https://www.dropbox.com/s/twvswlrix0kyqbw/MEASURESOFBIRTHANDDEATH.csv'

download.file(measures_url, measures_file, method="curl", extra='-L')

prevent_url = 'https://www.dropbox.com/s/qfaq98m9qpa9o01/PREVENTIVESERVICESUSE.csv'

download.file(prevent_url, prevent_file, method="curl", extra='-L')

relative_url = 'https://www.dropbox.com/s/p7lo5yi3grt6fq3/RELATIVEHEALTHIMPORTANCE.csv'

download.file(relative_url, relative_file, method="curl", extra='-L')

download.file(summary_url, summary_file, method="curl", extra='-L')

Side Note: All data is made available from www.data.gov (specifically: https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/community-health-status-indicators-chsi-to-combat-obesity-heart-disease-and-cancer/resource/6c143e9a-0c0f-486b-8cca-1415a2b91808).

www.data.gov is an online government database that compiles relevent statistics on the countywide level on a wide variety of items.
